properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - Telephone Service Alert
properties.Summary:
Description: Due to a wide spread wireless degradation, service for TELUS customers has been disrupted. This means that anyone in this area affected may be unable to contact Police, Fire and Ambulance by telephone if they have an emergency. The persons affected by this disruption should call 587-370-4681 should they require emergency services in the Taber or MD of Taber area. ### Telus has advised that there is a wide spread wireless degradation issue happening this morning. Telus teams are investigating. Telus clients may not be able to complete or connect to the network therefore not able to call 9 1 1.
Expires: 2020-04-07T10:26:09-06:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Town of Taber, 2020-03-31T10:24:19-06:00, NAADS-CA-AB-AEA1-6286
Area: MD of Taber
properties.Author: Town of Taber

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A weather system is spreading snow through the northern grainbelt this morning. Snow began in Meadow Lake overnight and will gradually diminish this afternoon. Total snowfall amounts for Meadow Lake are forecast to be in the 10 - 15 cm range. Snow will begin in Prince Albert this morning and continue throughout the day before tapering off later this afternoon. Snowfall amounts are forecast to be 10 cm in Prince Albert. Snow will be heavy at times resulting in reduced visibility. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Wreckhouse Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Prolonged Wreckhouse Winds expected Wednesday and Thursday. Strongest gusts: southeasterly near 110 km/h Time span: beginning Wednesday morning until at least part of Thursday. At that time winds are expected to become more east-northeast which is less favourable to enhanced Wreckhouse winds. ### Wreckhouse wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain fell early this morning in the Saskatoon area, causing icy road conditions, then at 7 a.m. it changed over to snow. Radar shows this area of freezing rain tracking east-northeast towards Melfort, Wakaw, and Humboldt. It will likely produce icy roads before transitioning to snow by early this afternoon. Wynyard plus areas east and south of there should receive mostly rain from this system. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow beginning this afternoon changing to rain Wednesday. Snowfall total: 5 to 10 cm. Rainfall total: 20 to 40 mm. Location: northeastern New Brunswick. Remarks: Periods of snow tonight will change to rain on Wednesday as temperatures rise above zero. An extended period of rain is then expected to last until Thursday night, when temperatures should fall below zero again. At this time, precipitation should change to flurries and taper off by Friday morning. Temperatures will remain above freezing through the overnight hours on Wednesday. The rain and mild temperatures could lead to significant melting of the snow pack and runoff. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A cold trough swinging over the central interior is giving snow, heavy at times, to the 100 Mile House region and Begbie Summit. Locally 9 cm of snow has already fallen and a further 5 cm is possible. The heavier snow is expected to ease later this afternoon. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Total snowfall: 25 to 35 cm. Locations: Hopedale to Makkovik. Time span: Overnight tonight to Thursday evening. Remarks: Significant snowfall and moderate winds will combine reduce visibility in blowing snow Wednesday and Thursday. Snow will be light tonight, but will increase in intensity on Wednesday morning. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 25 cm continues. A prolonged period of snowfall continues to impact communities in northern Manitoba. The heaviest snow has now tapered off, but a second impulse will be moving over northwestern regions tonight and through Wednesday. This next system is forecast to bring an additional 10 to 15 cm of snow. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall, combined with melting snow, is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. Between 25 and 40 millimetres of rain is expected beginning Wednesday morning through Thursday. ### Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
